Name: sql

Type: keyword

Syntax: sql [date]

Summary:
Specifies a <format> for the <convert> <command> that is compatible with
SQL database datetime columns.

Introduced: 10.0

OS: mac, windows, linux, ios, android

Platforms: desktop, server, mobile

Example:
convert the date && the time to sql date
put it into tTimestamp -- e.g. "2026-05-01 14:30:00"

Example:
convert tTimestamp from sql date to long date and long time

Example:
put "INSERT INTO log (created_at) VALUES ('" & tTimestamp & "')" into tSQL

Description:
Use the <sql> <keyword> with the <convert> <command> to work with dates
and times in a format that is directly compatible with SQL `DATETIME` and
`TIMESTAMP` column types (ISO 8601 combined date and time).

The <sql> date format is:

    YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS

where the date parts are separated by hyphens and the time parts are
separated by colons, with a single space between the date and the time.
For example, May 1 2026 at 2:30 PM is represented as:

    2026-05-01 14:30:00

The time is always in 24-hour format. Unlike the <internet> format, the
<sql> format does not include a time-zone offset; the stored value is
treated as local time, consistent with how most SQL databases handle
`DATETIME` columns.

You can use the optional `date` modifier (`sql date`) as an explicit
reminder that this is a date-and-time format; the two forms are
equivalent and produce the same result.

You can use the modifiers <long>, <short>, and <abbreviated> in
conjunction with the <sql> <keyword> without causing a
<error|script error>, but they have no effect on the resulting format.

>*Note:* The <sql> <keyword> is implemented internally as a
> <property> and appears in the <propertyNames>. However, it cannot be
> used as a <property> in an <expression>, nor with the <set> <command>.

